abstract: Let G be a connected graph and c a proper coloring of G. For i = 1; 2; : : : ; k define the color class Ci as the set of vertices receiving color i. The color code c�(v) of a vertex v in is the ordered k-tuple (d(v;C1); : : : ; d(v;Ck)) where (d(v;C1) is the distance of v to Ci. If all distinct vertices of G have distinct color codes, then c is called a locating-coloring of G . The locating-chromatic number of graph G, denoted by �L(G) is the smallest k such that G has a locating coloring with k colors. Let fu1; u2; : : : ; ung be some vertices on the outer cycle and fv1; v2; : : : ; vng be some vertices on the inner cycle, for n � 3.
